Abstract:
Inhalation of ash can be of great concern for affected communities, during and after
volcanic eruptions. Governmental and humanitarian agencies recommend and distribute a variety of
respiratory protection (RP), commonly surgical masks but, also, industry-certied N95-style masks.
However, there is currently no evidence on howwearable they are within affected populations or how
protective wearers perceive thembeing against volcanic ash (which will inuence the likelihood of
uptake of recommended interventions). Volunteers living near Mt. Sinabung, Sumatra, Indonesia,
participated in a eld wearability study, which included a high-efciency mask certied to industry
standards (N95-equiv.); a standard, pleated surgical mask (Surgical); a Basic at-fold mask (Flat-fold),
and the surgical mask plus a scarf tied over the top (Surgical Plus) to improve t. These types of RP
had all performed well during earlier laboratory ltration efciency tests. The N95-equiv. mask had
performed signicantly better than the other RP in the subsequent total inward leakage volunteer
trials, whilst the Flat-fold and Surgical masks performed poorly, letting in a third of PM
particles
(data published elsewhere). Thirty volunteers wore each mask for a 15-min walk before being asked to
rate the comfort, breathability and perceived protection and t of each. After wearing all of the masks,
volunteers compared and identied their preferred type of protection. The feedback received fromthe
volunteers suggested that the Surgical Plus and N95-equiv. masks were rated as being signicantly
hotter and more humid than other masks. The Flat-fold was rated to have better breathability than
the other masks. The N95-equiv. mask was ranked as providing the best level of effectiveness of the
four masks tested. Ultimately, when asked which type of mask they would choose to wear during
ashfall, 33%selected the Flat-fold mask due to its comfort and simplicity, with the Surgical Plus being
the least likely to be chosen of the four tested. The study ndings are of benet to agencies who
need to make informed decisions on the procurement and distribution of RP for use by those affected
in future eruptions and the provision of advice to communities on their usage.
